  "summary": "Six students approach the sage Pippalada with six profound questions (prashnas) about the origin of creation, prana, sleep and waking, the syllable Om, the five pranas, and the sixteen-part Purusha. Pippalada answers each in turn.",
  "total_verses": 67,
  "verses": [
    {
      "upanishad": "prashna",
      "verse_number": 1,
      "tags": [
        "prana",
        "rayi",
        "creation",
        "Prajapati"
      ],
      "sanskrit": "स होवाच — प्राणश्च रयिश्च प्रजापतिः सृष्टौ — तयोरन्यतरः प्राणः — आदित्यः ||१.४||",
      "transliteration": "sa hovāca — prāṇaś ca rayiś ca prajāpatiḥ sṛṣṭau — tayor anyataraḥ prāṇaḥ — ādityaḥ ||1.4||",
      "word_meanings": [
        {
          "word": "प्राणः",
          "meaning": "prana (the active, solar principle)"
        },
        {
          "word": "रयिः",
          "meaning": "rayi (the material, lunar principle)"
        },
        {
          "word": "प्रजापतिः",
          "meaning": "Prajapati (the Lord of creation)"
        },
        {
          "word": "सृष्टौ",
          "meaning": "created/projected"
        },
        {
          "word": "आदित्यः",
          "meaning": "the Sun"
        }
      ],
      "english_translation": "He said: Prajapati created prana and rayi (matter). Of these two, prana is the Sun.",
      "shankara_bhashya_sanskrit": "प्राणः — चेतनः सूर्यः। रयिः — अचेतना चन्द्रमाः। एतौ द्वौ सर्वस्य जगतः कारणम्।",
      "shankara_bhashya_english": "Shankara: Prana is the conscious solar principle; rayi is the inert lunar principle. These two are the cause of the entire world — the active and passive aspects of creation."
    },
    {
      "upanishad": "prashna",
      "verse_number": 2,
      "tags": [
        "Om",
        "Brahman",
        "higher lower",
        "meditation"
      ],
      "sanskrit": "ओमित्येतदक्षरमभिध्यायीत — एष ह वाव साधु कर्म करोति यः एनमभिध्यायीत ||५.२||",
      "transliteration": "om ity etad akṣaram abhidhyāyīta — eṣa ha vāva sādhu karma karoti yaḥ enam abhidhyāyīta ||5.2||",
      "word_meanings": [
        {
          "word": "ओम् इति एतत् अक्षरम्",
          "meaning": "this syllable Om"
        },
        {
          "word": "अभिध्यायीत",
          "meaning": "should meditate upon"
        },
        {
          "word": "साधु कर्म करोति",
          "meaning": "does good action"
        }
      ],
      "english_translation": "One should meditate on this syllable Om. Whoever meditates on it does good action.",
      "shankara_bhashya_sanskrit": "ओम् इति — प्रणवः परब्रह्मणः वाचकः। तम् अभिध्यायन् — उपासन् — साधु कर्म करोति — श्रेयः प्राप्नोति।",
      "shankara_bhashya_english": "Shankara: Om is the indicator of the supreme Brahman. One who meditates on Om attains the good — both the lower good of higher worlds and the highest good of liberation, depending on the depth of meditation."
    },
    {
      "upanishad": "prashna",
      "verse_number": 3,
      "tags": [
        "sixteen parts",
        "Purusha",
        "Self"
      ],
      "sanskrit": "कस्मिन्नु भगवो विज्ञाते सर्वमिदं विज्ञातं भवतीति ||६.१||",
      "transliteration": "kasmin nu bhagavo vijñāte sarvam idaṃ vijñātaṃ bhavatīti ||6.1||",
      "word_meanings": [
        {
          "word": "कस्मिन् विज्ञाते",
          "meaning": "by knowing what"
        },
        {
          "word": "सर्वम् इदम्",
          "meaning": "all this"
        },
        {
          "word": "विज्ञातम् भवति",
          "meaning": "becomes known"
        }
      ],
      "english_translation": "By knowing what, O Blessed One, does all this become known?",
      "shankara_bhashya_sanskrit": "कस्मिन् विज्ञाते — किं एकं ज्ञात्वा सर्वं ज्ञातं भवति — इति षष्ठः प्रश्नः।",
      "shankara_bhashya_english": "Shankara: This is the sixth and final question: by knowing what one thing does everything become known? The answer points to the Self (Atman) as the ground of all knowledge."
    },
    {
      "upanishad": "prashna",
      "verse_number": 4,
      "tags": [
        "prana",
        "sun",
        "moon",
        "creation",
        "Prajapati"
      ],
      "sanskrit": "आदित्यो ह वै प्राणः | रयिरेव चन्द्रमाः | यद्धैतत्सर्वं मूर्तं चामूर्तं च रयिरेव तत् ||१.५||",
      "transliteration": "ādityo ha vai prāṇaḥ | rayir eva candramāḥ | yad dhaitad sarvaṃ mūrtaṃ cāmūrtaṃ ca rayir eva tat ||1.5||",
      "word_meanings": [
        {
          "word": "आदित्यः प्राणः",
          "meaning": "the Sun is prana"
        },
        {
          "word": "रयिः चन्द्रमाः",
          "meaning": "the Moon is rayi (matter)"
        },
        {
          "word": "मूर्तम् च अमूर्तम्",
          "meaning": "the formed and the formless"
        },
        {
          "word": "रयिः एव तत्",
          "meaning": "that is rayi alone"
        }
      ],
      "english_translation": "The Sun is indeed prana; the Moon is indeed rayi. Whatever is formed and formless — all that is rayi alone.",
      "shankara_bhashya_sanskrit": "आदित्यः — सूर्यः — प्राणः — चेतनः। चन्द्रमाः — रयिः — अचेतनः। मूर्तम् अमूर्तम् — स्थूलसूक्ष्मम् — सर्वम् रयिः।",
      "shankara_bhashya_english": "Shankara: The Sun represents the conscious, active principle (prana); the Moon represents the material, passive principle (rayi). All formed and formless matter is rayi. This cosmic duality underlies all creation."
    },
    {
      "upanishad": "prashna",
      "verse_number": 5,
      "tags": [
        "prana",
        "five pranas",
        "Kashyapa",
        "question"
      ],
      "sanskrit": "कति ह वा अस्मिन् पुरुषे प्राणाः | कतर एते पुरुषं विधारयन्ति | कश्चैतेषां वरिष्ठ इति ||२.१||",
      "transliteration": "kati ha vā asmin puruṣe prāṇāḥ | katara ete puruṣaṃ vidhārayanti | kaś caitesāṃ variṣṭha iti ||2.1||",
      "word_meanings": [
        {
          "word": "कति प्राणाः",
          "meaning": "how many pranas"
        },
        {
          "word": "पुरुषम् विधारयन्ति",
          "meaning": "support the person"
        },
        {
          "word": "वरिष्ठः",
          "meaning": "the greatest among them"
        }
      ],
      "english_translation": "How many pranas are there in this person? Which of these support the person? And which among them is the greatest?",
      "shankara_bhashya_sanskrit": "कति प्राणाः — कियन्तः प्राणाः अस्मिन् शरीरे। कतरे विधारयन्ति — के शरीरं धारयन्ति। कः वरिष्ठः — कः प्रधानः।",
      "shankara_bhashya_english": "Shankara: The second question asks about the pranas — how many are there, which ones sustain the body, and which is the chief. Pippalada will answer that there are five pranas and that the chief prana (mukhya prana) is supreme."
    },
    {
      "upanishad": "prashna",
      "verse_number": 6,
      "tags": [
        "five pranas",
        "prana",
        "apana",
        "vyana",
        "udana",
        "samana"
      ],
      "sanskrit": "पञ्चैव प्राणाः | प्राणोऽपानो व्यान उदानः समानश्चेति ||२.३||",
      "transliteration": "pañcaiva prāṇāḥ | prāṇo'pāno vyāna udānaḥ samānaś ceti ||2.3||",
      "word_meanings": [
        {
          "word": "पञ्च प्राणाः",
          "meaning": "five pranas"
        },
        {
          "word": "प्राणः",
          "meaning": "upward breath"
        },
        {
          "word": "अपानः",
          "meaning": "downward breath"
        },
        {
          "word": "व्यानः",
          "meaning": "pervading breath"
        },
        {
          "word": "उदानः",
          "meaning": "upward-moving breath"
        },
        {
          "word": "समानः",
          "meaning": "equalizing breath"
        }
      ],
      "english_translation": "There are five pranas: prana, apana, vyana, udana, and samana.",
      "shankara_bhashya_sanskrit": "पञ्च प्राणाः — प्राणः — नासिकाग्रे वर्तते। अपानः — पायौ। व्यानः — सर्वशरीरे। उदानः — कण्ठे। समानः — नाभौ।",
      "shankara_bhashya_english": "Shankara: The five pranas have different locations and functions. Prana operates at the nostrils (inhalation). Apana operates at the lower body (elimination). Vyana pervades the whole body. Udana operates at the throat (speech, death). Samana operates at the navel (digestion)."
    },
    {
      "upanishad": "prashna",
      "verse_number": 7,
      "tags": [
        "prana",
        "chief",
        "sun",
        "fire",
        "all senses"
      ],
      "sanskrit": "एष ह वाव वरिष्ठः यः प्राणः | एष एव सर्वाणि भूतानि धारयति ||२.१३||",
      "transliteration": "eṣa ha vāva variṣṭhaḥ yaḥ prāṇaḥ | eṣa eva sarvāṇi bhūtāni dhārayati ||2.13||",
      "word_meanings": [
        {
          "word": "एषः वरिष्ठः",
          "meaning": "this one is the greatest"
        },
        {
          "word": "यः प्राणः",
          "meaning": "which is prana (the chief)"
        },
        {
          "word": "सर्वाणि भूतानि धारयति",
          "meaning": "supports all beings"
        }
      ],
      "english_translation": "This one is indeed the greatest — the chief prana. This one alone supports all beings.",
      "shankara_bhashya_sanskrit": "एषः प्राणः — मुख्यप्राणः — वरिष्ठः — सर्वेषाम् प्रधानः। एषः सर्वाणि भूतानि धारयति — सर्वेषाम् जीवनाधारः।",
      "shankara_bhashya_english": "Shankara: The chief prana (mukhya prana) is the greatest — it is the life-force that sustains all beings. All the other pranas are its manifestations. Without the chief prana, no being can live."
    },
    {
      "upanishad": "prashna",
      "verse_number": 8,
      "tags": [
        "Om",
        "A U M",
        "three matras",
        "meditation",
        "Brahman"
      ],
      "sanskrit": "अकार उ वै सर्वा वाक् | सैषा स्पर्शोष्मभिर्व्यज्यमाना बहुधा भवति ||५.५||",
      "transliteration": "akāra u vai sarvā vāk | saiṣā sparśoṣmabhir vyajyamānā bahudhā bhavati ||5.5||",
      "word_meanings": [
        {
          "word": "अकारः सर्वा वाक्",
          "meaning": "the letter A is all speech"
        },
        {
          "word": "स्पर्शोष्मभिः",
          "meaning": "by consonants and sibilants"
        },
        {
          "word": "व्यज्यमाना",
          "meaning": "being manifested"
        },
        {
          "word": "बहुधा भवति",
          "meaning": "becomes manifold"
        }
      ],
      "english_translation": "The letter A is indeed all speech. Being manifested by consonants and sibilants, it becomes manifold.",
      "shankara_bhashya_sanskrit": "अकारः — सर्वासाम् वर्णानाम् आधारः। सर्वा वाक् — सर्वे शब्दाः — अकारात् एव।",
      "shankara_bhashya_english": "Shankara: The letter A is the basis of all speech — all sounds are modifications of A. Similarly, Om (which begins with A) is the basis of all Vedic knowledge. This explains why Om is the most fundamental mantra."
    },
    {
      "upanishad": "prashna",
      "verse_number": 9,
      "tags": [
        "sixteen parts",
        "Purusha",
        "Self",
        "rivers"
      ],
      "sanskrit": "यथा नद्यः स्यन्दमानाः समुद्रेऽस्तं गच्छन्ति | नामरूपे विहाय | तथा विद्वान् नामरूपाद्विमुक्तः परात्परं पुरुषमुपैति दिव्यम् ||६.५||",
      "transliteration": "yathā nadyaḥ syandamānāḥ samudre'staṃ gacchanti | nāmarūpe vihāya | tathā vidvān nāmarūpād vimuktaḥ parātparaṃ puruṣam upaiti divyam ||6.5||",
      "word_meanings": [
        {
          "word": "नद्यः समुद्रे अस्तम् गच्छन्ति",
          "meaning": "rivers merge into the ocean"
        },
        {
          "word": "नामरूपे विहाय",
          "meaning": "leaving behind name and form"
        },
        {
          "word": "परात्परम् पुरुषम्",
          "meaning": "the Person beyond the beyond"
        },
        {
          "word": "दिव्यम् उपैति",
          "meaning": "attains the divine"
        }
      ],
      "english_translation": "As rivers flowing merge into the ocean, leaving behind name and form — so the wise one, freed from name and form, attains the divine Person who is beyond the beyond.",
      "shankara_bhashya_sanskrit": "नद्यः — समुद्रे लीयन्ते — नामरूपे विहाय। तथा विद्वान् — ब्रह्मज्ञः — नामरूपात् विमुक्तः — परात्परम् पुरुषम् उपैति।",
      "shankara_bhashya_english": "Shankara: Just as rivers lose their individual names and forms when they merge into the ocean, the wise one loses individual identity when merging into Brahman. This is liberation — the dissolution of the separate self into the infinite."
    },
